<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he Relatives &amp; Residents Association</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CQ 11)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">About R&amp;RA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Relatives &amp; Residents Association (R&amp;RA) speaks up and speaks out on behalf of older people in care homes. It is the only national charity for older people providing a daily helpline which concentrates entirely on residential care for this age group.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA was founded to campaign for a better quality of life for older people living in care homes. By using the unique perspectives of relatives and residents, we work in harness with others to help improve service and standards. We also try to influence policy and practice by reflecting the experience of our members and callers who use our daily Helpline and thus can make evidence based comments on the case we make, the research and training we carry out and the policies we advocate.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We provide support and information through our Helpline and enable older people and their relatives make better informed decisions about looking for a home, explain their rights under guidance and regulations, and the benefits and standards they should expect.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We also act as a listening ear to help support families and individuals at what is often a time of crisis and trauma for them, when it becomes apparent that a partner, parent or friend can no longer live at home. We also help them when there are difficulties and complaints about the standard of care and often act as brokers between the relative/concerned individual and the care home.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our comments are based on our Helpline service and our activities, including training, research and feedback about the reality of daily life in care homes for older people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inevitably, our Helpline service is sought by relatives experiencing problems within care homes.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, we acknowledge there are many homes where very good care is provided and that there are hundreds of frontline staff who are doing their utmost to provide the best quality of life they can for older people living in residential and nursing homes. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In our evidence to the committee for the 2012 accountability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hearing, we said; </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQC is not acting as an agent for improvement as required in their governing legislation;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQC does not have sufficient expertise in the care home sector;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQC’s strategy should build in the capability to inspect care homes at least twice a year;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* performance measures for care homes should focus on improvement in the health, safety and well-being of residents;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* there should be two inspections of care homes per year;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* a focus on a few selected standards only is negligent;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* specialists with expertise in care homes should be recruited to inspect care homes;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQC appears to be taking steps to being a learning organisation, but they have a long way to go;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQC could reduce the burdens on care homes for older people by becoming a reliable and trusted organisation;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQC should carry out an evaluation of its priorities and inspection methodology;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* CQCs regulatory regime should be specifically tailored to meet the needs of each sector;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* the DH should improve its capability and expertise on the regulation of safety and quality; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">* the CQC website should not allow care homes to expunge their (often poor) records by changing the name under which the provider is registered.</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While there have been some changes for the better, a number of our chief concerns remain.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inspections remain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">too infrequent;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CQC’s inspection methodology remains inadequate;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">enforcement action is lacking;</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inspectors of care homes often</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lack expertise in the care home sector, in particular in care for older people;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inspection reports lack sufficient information for the public to judge how a home is performing and for prospective residents and their families to choose a home that will meet their needs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA acknowledge the huge challenge facing regulatory bodies following the various inquiries and studies published over recent months including Winterbourne View and the Francis Report.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We welcome the appointment of Andrea Sutcliffe as the new Chief Inspector of Social Care and look forward to a similar drive to overhaul inspection of care homes as there is currently to improve inspections of hospitals.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Frequency of inspections</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As part of that work, we would urge CQC to increase the numbers of inspections to two a year, with at least one inspection being unannounced.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This was the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mandatory minimum from 1988 until 2006/7 and was dispensed with because of budget cuts imposed on the regulator, rather than because there was clear evidence that a “risk based” approach had been shown to be more effective.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have consistently argued for two annual inspections because the evidence from our Helpline tells us that infrequent and superficial inspections result in poor care going unnoticed and unchecked.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We remain of the view that because a care home is a person’s home, their welfare and safety cannot be effectively safeguarded through an annual inspection alone.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We continue to be concerned about those older people (around 20%) who have no kith or kin or are not visited for a variety of reasons, many of whom are self-funders and who do not come under the umbrella of responsibility of local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A home classed as “good” could remain uninspected for a long period, also bearing in mind, the average age and condition of older people in care homes, several “generations” of residents would never experience an inspection.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Providers who perform well should also have an up to date report available to show to prospective residents and to commissioners. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CQC takes the view that inspection rates should be based on the risk involved.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Up to now, it appears to us, and is evidenced by our Helpline, inquests and frequent media reports of failing homes that the current “risk based” approach is deeply flawed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CQC maintains that additional inspections will not add any value but have not evidenced this view.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Neither have they clearly spelled out what the “risk based” approach entails and how bad care has to become before an inspection is triggered.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA maintains that the adoption of the risk based approach, particularly coupled with CQC’s generic approach over the last four or so years, has been ineffectual.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA has a number of trustees and volunteers who are former inspectors and still in touch with the current practice.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">They and the evidence of our Helpline suggest that practice in many homes has become poorer over the last few years partly due to lack of training, inadequate staffing ratios, high manager vacancies and the increased vulnerability and dependence of residents in care homes for older people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CQC’s current risk based approach is not working since its premise is based on waiting for things to go wrong, rather than preventing poor care arising in the first place.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA have no confidence in CQCs current “risk based” approach to determining inspection which is letting down older people in care homes throughout the country.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inspection methodology</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CQC’s business plan is ambitious for inspection of hospitals and rightly so.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">They want to ‘improve the safety and quality of care in NHS acute hospitals and mental health trusts by changing the way we inspect them’.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The business plan also says they will ‘Identify, predict and respond more quickly to services that are failing or likely to fail by using data, intelligence and evidence in a more sophisticated way’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA’s view is that plans to inspect and drive up the quality of care in care homes should be equally ambitious.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Development of fundamental standards for care homes by CQC may be regarded as a positive step.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, without sufficient data, or tested methodology, the standards will not deliver improved care of older people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Fundamental standards are a good starting point but they must be supported by statements which are explicit, measurable and specific to the type of care being provided, acknowledging that the essential requirements for good quality residential and nursing care will be different for each client group. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Data collection and intelligence gathering for care homes needs to be far more sophisticated than at present since there may be little or no information from some services.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, gathering data by itself will not be enough: there also needs to be analysis. We have seen in recent times that death rates of people in care homes have not been analysed sufficiently carefully.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Such analyses could well have revealed that people were dying much earlier than expected.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">David Behan, on the Panorama programme broadcast in June 2013 (in which R&amp;RA clients were featured), gave an undertaking that death rates would be looked at as an indicator of the quality of care being provided. This followed an analysis by Professor Brian </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Jarman</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which showed that death rates in The Poplars (one of the homes featured in Panorama) were at the high end of what would be regarded as normal.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The importance of death rates is given even more weight by the on-going inquest into the Orchid View Home in Sussex where 19 deaths were unexplained.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Enforcement Action</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CQC has itself acknowledged that use of enforcement action in previous times has been insufficient.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA welcomes their intention to bear down on homes that lack managers as indicated in the minutes of their board meeting of September 2013.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We would also welcome a more robust approach to carrying out enforcement action on homes where standards are clearly failing.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We note there have been very few instances where registration has been removed as a result of inspection findings. Where homes have closed, it has more likely been as a result of local authorities’ refusing admissions, or removing their residents and making clear why, or by the action of the HSE and other enforcement agencies.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We know that closing homes is a drastic measure and should not be carried out lightly.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, we see little or no evidence that CQC is acting, as David Behan has said, to root out poor care or cause poor providers to cease to exist. We would welcome fresh thinking on the use of enforcement powers as one of the tools for driving up quality of care.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inspectors lacking expertise</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;RA welcomes CQCs programme to introduce specialist inspectors, experts and experts by experience.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We remain concerned that recruitment of expertise in care of older people in residential and nursing care is still thin on the ground and we would like to see CQC publish data on the number and range of experts and specialists it has recruited or intends to recruit.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our intelligence is that specialist teams for care homes are not yet fully in place.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In CQCs response to the 2012 accountability hearing, CQC said it would consider working with other agencies to carry out inspections and make greater use of reviews carried out by others, including Monitor, local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Healthwatch</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and overview and scrutiny committee.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While on the surface this appears sensible, use of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Healthwatch</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in care homes cannot take the place of inspection and can only be regarded as an avenue for intelligence gathering rather than replacing the regulatory duty of CQC.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We see a stark contradiction between on the one hand, strengthening CQC inspection teams with experts, and yet relying on reviews carried out by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Healthwatch</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> who would not necessarily have the knowledge or background to provide useful or consistent information. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of information in inspection reports</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Alongside the development of fundamental standards, CQC must develop their reports of inspection findings so the public have an accurate and up to date understanding of the care provision within homes.</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We note the recommendations and reservations of the report into ratings by the Nuffield Trust and agree that a rating </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">system is unlikely to be useful on its own in spotting lapses in the quality of care. We also agree that there are risks that rating systems would become discredited by a lapse in care in a provider rated as ‘good’ or ‘excellent’.</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ratings, therefore, are only worthwhile when backed up by regular robust inspection and comprehensive and readable reports.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our view is that the current style of reports is not good enough, based as they are on checking against a few standards only.</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">What the public and prospective care home residents need are inspection reports that tell them at least the following:</span><br /><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1. How much time was spent in the home? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2. How many inspectors? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3. The name of the inspector </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">4. The time of the inspection </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">5. How many relatives were spoken with or involved in the inspection via a survey? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">6. Whether there is a registered manager in post? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">7. If so, the name and qualifications of the manager </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">8. If none, to say so and give the reasons </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">9. Plus provider’s plan to deal with the vacancy and appoint a new manager </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">10. Which regulations were found to have been breached during the inspection? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">11. The specific powers being used to take enforcement action </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">12. Plus the time-table for this </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">13. Which regulations are still in breach from any previous inspections and reasons, if any, for any continued breach </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">14. If so, what further enforcement action will be taken? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">15. The number of complaints received, what they were about and whether or not they have been resolved? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">16. Any safeguarding concerns and if so, what about? and to whom referred? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2.55pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">17. Some detail about the staffing ratio in the home and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">18. Whether there are any stimulating activities</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Calls to our Helpline show that relatives not only have concern about their own family member, but also have concerns about care in general, including the care of other residents. Also, they have current and useful intelligence about staffing levels, food and meal-times, as well as the management and running of the home. We should like to see all relatives regularly surveyed as part of the inspection process, which would have the additional benefit of alerting them to the existence of the regulator, a practice used (but subsequently discarded) by CSCI.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Current practice is for some inspectors to speak only to any relatives who might be present at the time of the inspection which is just too hit and miss to be regarded as a professional approach. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> 18 April 2013 PQ WA total number of warning notices issued by CQC in 2012/13 was 1178 for all regulated services, approx. 35000 c3.5% of the total.</span></p></body></html>